    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="714"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d714">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 888.111/69.]</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.—Paraphrases]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Port au Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 21, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>On May 18 the French war vessel <hi rend="italic">Descartes</hi> arrived here and
                    will remain pending the settlement of the Syrian question, as I am told by an
                    employee of the French Legation, which is protecting Turkish interests. The
                    Haitian Government seems determined to close, on May 31, all stores operated by
                    Syrians, Ottoman subjects.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Furniss</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
